{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Renamed files appear in their own category and are not also counted as a deletion plus an addition.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"The real failure boundary is the CLI’s interaction with an actual git repo and git’s rename detection behavior. Mocked or fixture-based parsing can miss failures from real git command flags/thresholds and status output nuances.","test_description":"Create a temp git repo, commit a file, rename it, run the CLI against real repo state, and assert the report shows the file only in `renamed` and not in `added`/`deleted`.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.25,"System":0.7,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"Diffs that include binary files do not cause the tool to crash; binary files are counted in the output.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This depends on real git diff behavior for binary content and real process/encoding handling. Mocking diff output can hide decode/parsing crashes that happen only with actual binary diffs.","test_description":"Create a temp git repo with a committed binary file change, run the CLI, assert process exits successfully and binary changes are included in counts.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.9,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"Running the tool on a repository that has no commits yet produces an empty report rather than an error.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"The failure mode is tied to unborn-HEAD repository state and actual git command behavior (often non-zero exits/special messages). That state is best validated with a real initialized repo and CLI execution.","test_description":"Initialize a new git repo with no commits, run the CLI, and assert success with an empty structured report instead of an exception/error output.